<h1 id="Part-1:-A-Philosophy-Behind-Clustering">Part 1: A Philosophy Behind Clustering<a class="anchor-link" href="#Part-1:-A-Philosophy-Behind-Clustering">¶</a></h1><p>Tennis is always looking for the next Federer, the next Djokovic, Nadal, Sampras, or whomever.</p>
<p>So what defines the <em>next</em> so-and-so? While it depends on the context, usually it means one of two things: the next person to match their results, or the next person to play with a similar "style". We already have many ways to evaluate who is the best, and predicting future stars with any level of certainty is a poor prospect: after all, it feels like we've been waiting for the next generation to arrive for well over a generation. While match commentary often mentions style, I'm not sure I've really seen any analysis grouping players based on style.</p>
<p>Grigor Dimitrov, and just about every other rising player with a one-handed backhand, was at one point proclaimed the next Federer. Unfortunately, much of the news covering Dimitrov called him "Baby Fed" and then proceeded to unfavorably compare him with the greatest players of all time. While I find that commentary mean-spirited, I also think it misses the point: outcomes and style are not the same thing, and more often than not, they should be considered separately (or as I will argue, they interact to approach an equilibrium). It seems what these reporters are really upset about is that playing like Federer, or anyone else, is not enough to match their greatness. Turns out, winning is more complicated than that.</p>
<p>There's also tons of articles, like <a href="https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/the-serve-and-volley-works-but-womens-tennis-players-arent-using-it/">this one</a> from FiveThirtyEight <sup>[1]</sup>, that commit what I consider to be a related error. They look at the success rate of a tactic (serve-and-volley in the WTA), observe that it is high, and then lament that players aren't using the tactic enough. There's a seductive appeal to this view of the sport; after all, who doesn't want to discover the single tactic that improves the results of any player in the entire world? But the sport probably doesn't work like that. There are plenty of players with strong incentives to excel at tennis, they have a lot of shared information, and they all have different abilities for various skills. If there was one tactic to rule them all, it's likely that someone might have found it, other players might have noticed, and the edge would have diminished as other players used and/or countered it. We'd also expect certain players to struggle with implementing the tactic and seek out new ones for an edge. It seems unlikely that tennis will reach a stable equilibrium where all players should use precisely the same strategy. Even if there was a single dominant strategy, we as tennis fans should be more hesitant to claim that we've found it, as games with uniform, obvious optimal strategies are usually less interesting.</p>
<p>This is not to say that tennis players make perfect decisions. I just think we should start by considering styles as self-selecting: players are likely to migrate to styles that fit their skills. That doesn't mean that this self-selection is perfect, but it does mean we should be more charitable before we say that someone is playing with the wrong tactics. It's plausible that the tennis player who avoids coming to net might just think that her net play is bad, even though it is pretty good. But it's more likely, or at least more charitable, to start with the assumption that she doesn't come to net because she is correct that her net play is not as strong as other parts of her game. It's even possible that coming to net is successful precisely because only the players who are best at net use the tactic, players only come to net in moments when their court position is particularly strong, or because it is used so rarely that it has a success rate that could not be matched by those players coming to net more often.</p>
<blockquote><p>Federer comes to net a lot and it seems to work for him. If, in response, you increase the frequency with which you come to net, and it doesn't pan out, you should ask yourself:</p>
<ol>
<li>"Is Federer better than me at <em>volleying</em>?" (...probably)</li>
<li>"Is Federer better than me at <em>identifying</em> the correct opportunity to come to net?" (...probably)</li>
<li>"Is Federer better than me at <em>creating</em> opportunities to come to net?" (...probably)</li>
</ol>
<p>It may still be the case that you should come to net more, but you should at least consider those questions, or ones like them, and gather more evidence.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>So, what is the <em>actual point</em> of clustering styles?
Really the point of any clustering is to make sense of a world with lots of objects. We do this by creating a few groups whose members are similar to each other and dissimilar to members of other groups. This is simply an exercise in creating archetypes. Once we've made our groups, we can characterize their defining features, look at the members of the groups, use the groups in other analyses, and see if there are differences in outcomes. Only then can we start asking chicken-and-egg outcome questions (does being a good player put you in this group, or does being in this group make you a good player?) But often the goal is simply, "this space is too complex, can we make it simpler to intuit?"</p>
<p>As someone who has read this far, you'll probably enjoy reading this article more than the average person who dropped out. That's self-selection at work.</p>
<h1 id="Part-2:-A-Look-at-Overall-Service-Placement-Patterns-in-the-ATP">Part 2: A Look at Overall Service Placement Patterns in the ATP<a class="anchor-link" href="#Part-2:-A-Look-at-Overall-Service-Placement-Patterns-in-the-ATP">¶</a></h1><p>This analysis is going to cluster individual players in the ATP by where they choose to serve. I've selected the ATP for three reasons:</p>
<ol>
<li>ATP matches at slams are played best of 5 sets, whereas WTA matches are best of 3 sets. This creates a larger sample size of points with known service placement, which I only have for a few tournaments.</li>
<li>Men's singles is a simpler game than women's singles, and more of it can be explained by strength of serves. While this can make men's singles less interesting to watch, it makes interpreting service patterns much easier.</li>
<li>The list of players near the top of men's singles has been more stable than the list of players at the top of women's singles over the last few years. This means casual observers will have name recognition for more of the top players, making cluster assignments and narratives a bit easier to digest.</li>
</ol>
<p>I'm going to start by looking at where individual players choose to serve. Next, I'm going to create clusters of players that make similar choices with their service placement. I'll then take a look at choices of the average player in each cluster, as well as all individual players grouped by their cluster. I'll conclude by trying to pull out some basic narratives for the decisions made by players in each cluster, and we'll see some sensible patterns emerge in how players approach their service games. While none of the input variables are really outcome variables <sup>[2]</sup>, you'll see that outcomes can help us understand the patterns we observe.</p>

The raw data used is Slam point-by-point data, obtained from <a href="https://github.com/JeffSackmann">his GitHub page</a>. I have performed some preprocessing that is not shown in this article.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Below there are two complementary heatmaps about Service Placement Patterns. They may look complex at first, but the organization is intutive:</p>
<ul>
<li>Each row is a single player.</li>
<li>There are four sets of five columns per heatmap. Each set of five splits the service box into the following vertical sections: wide, body/wide, body, body/center, center.<ul>
<li>The left ten columns are for first serves, and the right ten are for second serves.  Each column shows the frequency of serves in that direction. They are laid out spatially, as if you were returning the serve. For each serve number:<ul>
<li>The left five columns are for the ad court, from wide to body to center (T).</li>
<li>The second five columns are for the deuce court, from center (T) to body to wide.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>There are two heatmaps:<ul>
<li>The left heatmap is relative to the population: red cells signify serving to that location above average, and blue signifies serving there below average. The average value of each column across all players is 0, and the standard deviation is 1.</li>
<li>The right heatmap is absolute: darker shades of green signify serving to that location more often. The cells for a single player on the absolute heatmap sum to 4, because each set of 5 cells sums to 1.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<p>Two basic patterns stick out in this visualization:</p>
<ul>
<li>On first serves, players mostly serve either wide or down the center. They are less likely to serve between wide and body and between body and center, and least likely to serve at the body.</li>
<li>On second serves, players are more likely to serve into the body, particularly the body on the backhand side.</li>
</ul>
<p>Neither of these is a particularly surprising strategy. On first serve, it makes sense to be aggressive. On second, it makes sense to be more conservative and just hit to the opponent's weaker shot (often the backhand).</p>
<p>However, we also see plenty of variation around these dominant strategies. That's especially apparent when we look at service placement relative to the other players in the sample.</p>
<p>I'd like to look at one other broad pattern at the population level: the correlation between different service placements. We know that there is going to be considerable negative correlation for competing service locations (serves on the same serve number on the same side of the court). This is simply because the rates of serving into each vertical slice must sum to 1; serving down the center more necessarily means that the rate of serving to other parts of the service box goes down.</p>
<p>The figure below is a correlation matrix for all twenty serve types (first/second) (ad/deuce) (five directions). I've again separated the serve types into four groups of five directions. Each cell shows the correlation of the frequency of the serve type on the y axis with the one on the x axis. The top left to bottom right diagonal is an axis of symmetry, and all values along the diagonal are 1 by definition. Deeper red values signify stronger positive correlation, whereas deeper blue values signify stronger negative correlation.</p>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We see a number of interesting patterns here. I will discuss a few as an example of how to look at this particular data. Take your time examining the figure, these types of relations are central to this analysis.</p>
<ol>
<li>Serving wide on first serve on the ad court is most positively correlated with serving down the center on first serve in the deuce court. Assuming a right-handed opponent, these are both serves to the returner's backhand.</li>
<li>Serving down the center on first serve on the ad court is most positively correlated with serving wide on first serve in the deuce court. Assuming a right-handed opponent, these are both serves to the returner's forehand.</li>
<li>On first serves, serves into the body are most positively correlated with serves close to the body (BodyWide and BodyCenter).</li>
<li>Serving wide on first serve is positively correlated with serving wide on second serve. Serving down the center on first serve is also positively correlated with serving down the center on second serve.</li>
</ol>
<p>What we see here is that even at the population level there is strong correlation between service placement patterns across courts (Ad/Deuce) and across serve number (first/second).</p>
<h1 id="Part-3:-Dimensionality-Reduction-for-Service-Placement-Patterns">Part 3: Dimensionality Reduction for Service Placement Patterns<a class="anchor-link" href="#Part-3:-Dimensionality-Reduction-for-Service-Placement-Patterns">¶</a></h1><blockquote><p>Note: If you are not particularly interested in the details of dimensionality reduction and why it is important for clustering, you can skip to Part 4.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now we must address the effect of correlation on clustering. Clustering and correlation are two distinct concepts that are easily confused. When clustering, we are looking for specific regions of space with high population density. When we are looking at correlation we are searching for relations between variables that generally hold for the entire population.</p>
<blockquote><p>A two dimensional dataset can have have strong or weak correlation, and it can exhibit strong or weak clustering. All four combinations are possible:</p>
<ol>
<li>strong correlation and strong clustering</li>
<li>strong correlation and weak clustering</li>
<li>weak correlation and strong clustering</li>
<li>weak correlation and weak clustering.</li>
</ol>
<p>Put another way, correlation is about population level tendencies, whereas clustering is about unique tendencies within specific groups. The two should be considered independently.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>However, our ability to find clusters in high dimensional data <em>is affected</em> by correlation between variables. Suppose I was trying to find clusters with three variables and that I care about all three variables equally. When I evaluate how far points are from each other, I'm going to factor in the scale of each variable, simply because a difference of 1 in one variable might not be as meaningful as a difference of 1 in another variable. This is why I always standardize my data before clustering.</p>
<p>Now let's say I start with my same three variables (call them A, B, and C), but this time I add a fourth variable that is exactly the same (perfectly correlated) as the first variable (call it A2). The new variable doesn't add any information, but it completely messes up my scaling because a difference of 1 in A is also a difference of 1 in A2. That's basically doubling the weight of variable A. In practice, we don't intentionally add redundant variables to our datasets, but adding weakly correlated variables can have the same effect of skewing the importance of certain features when clustering. When clustering, we generally don't want correlated variables.</p>
<blockquote><p>Keen observers will note that each set of 5 service directions (<em>FirstAdWide</em>, <em>FirstAdBodyWide</em>, <em>FirstAdBody</em>, <em>FirstAdBodyCenter</em>, <em>FirstAdCenter</em>) has this issue. These are simply the percent of <em>nth</em> serves hit in that direction, so each set of five variables sums to one. That's a pretty obvious source of perfect correlation; you could perfectly recreate one variable from the other four. That should sound like I am doing precisely what I don't want to be doing. But just removing one variable from each set of 5 wouldn't solve the issue; the four remaining variables are still correlated with eachother and with serve directions in other situations.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>If I wanted uncorrelated variables, or just weakly correlated ones, I could carefully pick and choose them based on my knowledge of the meaning of each variable. That's a pretty intuitive approach, and one people use implicitly, but it would be pretty challenging and would take a long time. Instead, I could actually measure the correlation between the variables and then use that to manually select my variables. That might be more rigorous, but it's still going to be quite the headache.</p>
<p>This is where Principle Component Analysis comes in. PCA will transform <em>n</em> original variables into <em>n</em> new variables with the following properties:</p>
<ul>
<li>The new variables are linear combinations of the original variables</li>
<li>The new variables are uncorrelated</li>
<li>The new variables are sorted by the fraction of variance that they capture</li>
<li>The new variables preserve all of the information of the original variables</li>
</ul>
<p>Each principle component is going to be harder to interpret than the original variables, but it will be much easier to work with when clustering.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [8]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">create_principle_components</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">):</span>

<p>These are called the loadings for each variable. They are the weights used with each original variable in the construction of the new variables. <p>Now I can drop the dimensions that explain less variation in the data and try to see any clustering. I'm going to visualize this with a pairplot below, using the first 6 principle components. I will use 6 principle components for the rest of this article.</p>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>There's definitely <em>some</em> clustering, though it isn't as beautiful as examples in textbooks. But it's also hard to think in 6 dimensions, so I'm going to let my clustering algorithm be the judge of how to cluster this data.</p>
<h1 id="Part-4:-Clustering-Players-by-Service-Placement-Patterns">Part 4: Clustering Players by Service Placement Patterns<a class="anchor-link" href="#Part-4:-Clustering-Players-by-Service-Placement-Patterns">¶</a></h1><p>Now that I have my transformed variables of interest, it's time to do some clustering.</p>
<p>I'm going to use k means clustering on the first 6 principle components.</p>
<p>K-means clustering is an unsupervised learning technique for grouping <em>n</em> observations into <em>k</em> clusters so that each observation belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean. It is a way to group similar observations based on chosen cluster variables.
K-means clustering chooses cluster assignments to minimize the within-cluster sum of squares:</p>
<blockquote><p>Within Cluster Sum of Squares =   (x-)^2</p>
</blockquote>
<p>where x is the value for the individual observation and  is the average value for the cluster to which it is assigned. This is often written with two summation signs: the first sums all the clusters and the second sums all the elements in that cluster. Moving observation A from cluster X to cluster Y changes the cluster mean for both clusters X and Y. This can alter the accuracy within both clusters.</p>
<p>The basic algorithm for k-means clustering is an iterative process consisting of two steps :</p>
<ol>
<li>Assign each observation to the cluster with the nearest mean (least Euclidean distance when clustering by multiple variables).</li>
<li>Update the mean values for each cluster.</li>
</ol>
<p>This iterative process continues until the within-cluster sum of squares converges to a local minimum. This algorithm may find a local optimum that is not the global optimum.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [14]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># performs k means clustering for a single value of k, and optionally shows clustered pairplot</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">k</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">plot_clusters</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">kmeans</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">KMeans</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_clusters</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">k</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_init</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">random_state</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">21</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="c1">#display clustering and AIC</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">plot_clusters</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'k is: '</span>
              <span class="o">+</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">k</span><span class="p">)</span>
              <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">' and AIC is: '</span>
              <span class="o">+</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">kmeans</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">inertia_</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">k</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="p">)))</span>
             <span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Cluster'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">kmeans</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">labels_</span>
        <span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">style</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'ticks'</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pairplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">hue</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'Cluster'</span><span class="p">,</span> 
                     <span class="nb">vars</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">col</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">col</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">col</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">'Cluster'</span><span class="p">],</span>
                     <span class="n">palette</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'husl'</span>
                    <span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
        <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">drop</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Cluster'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">kmeans</span>

<span class="c1"># repeatedly perform k means clustering for shifting values of k</span>
<span class="c1"># select value of k that minimizes AIC as optimal</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">cluster_shifting_k</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">max_k</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">plot_clusters</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">plot_AICs</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">aics</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
    <span class="n">kmeans_list</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
    <span class="n">df_std</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">standardize</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">num_dimensions</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df_std</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1">#pick optimal value of k by minimizing AIC for 1<=k<=max_k</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">k</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">max_k</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="n">kmeans_list</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df_std</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">k</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">plot_clusters</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">plot_clusters</span><span class="p">))</span>

<p>Before I actually cluster the servers, I need a strategy for selection the number of clusters (<em>k</em>). I've considered two basic approaches:</p>
<ol>
<li>Pick a number for <em>k</em> based on my expertise</li>
<li>Try to get a value for <em>k</em> based on the data</li>
</ol>
<p>In truth, there's a lot of approaches for determining the correct value of <em>k</em>, and I'm not particualrly interested in finding the perfect methodology for this article. Generally I like to use the value of <em>k</em> that minimizes the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC). The AIC is an information criterion that rewards a better fit of the data and penalizes the inclusion of more parameters in the model (increases in <em>k</em>). I find it to be a reasonable starting point for model selection when cross validation is not logical or feasible. The AIC for k means clustering is calculated as:</p>
<blockquote><p>AIC of k means clustering = Sum Squared Error + 2 (number of clusters) (dimensionality)</p>
</blockquote>

</div>

<p>This figure is almost identical to the one at the beginning of the article, except players are sorted into clusters. <sup>[3]</sup> We can see that clustering makes this information much easier to digest. For example, the first cluster has five players, including Kei Nishikori, Pablo Carreno Busta, and David Ferrer. These players hit to the body on first serve much more often than the rest of the tour.</p>
<p>Some of the clusters have more players than others, and some of the narratives for each cluster are more clear than others. I show the same type of figure below, except each row is the average for players within the cluster, and I've added a narrative label for each. <sup>[4]</sup></p>
<blockquote><p>The narratives are my interpretation of the clusters I've obtained. Creating narratives has two basic sources of error:</p>
<ol>
<li>My biases are going to impact the candidate narratives that I do and don't accept for each cluster.</li>
<li>These narratives are a simplification of more complex data. Some narratives will fit their clusters better than others, and some players fit their clusters better than others.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [19]:</div>

<h2 id="The-Service-Placement-Narratives">The Service Placement Narratives<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-Service-Placement-Narratives">¶</a></h2><blockquote><p>The narratives below are relative to other players on the tour. The dominant paradigm in the ATP is serving for the lines on first and serving more conservatively to the backhand on second.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3 id="Body-on-First,-Backhand-on-Second">Body on First, Backhand on Second<a class="anchor-link" href="#Body-on-First,-Backhand-on-Second">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Kei Nishikori, David Ferrer</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [21]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plot_single_cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">subset</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">cluster_labels</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]])</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Successful players with comparably weak serves (in terms of pace and/or placement) are likely successful in other facets of the game. Knowing the modern men's game, that facet is probably extended baseline rallies. The body serve is a respectable way to get the point started while limiting your opponent's ability to hit an offensive return. When serving with less pop (like for a second serve), biasing the serve to the opponent's backhand helps minimize the risk of punishing forehand returns.</p>
<h3 id="Body-Forehand-on-First,-Body-on-Second">Body Forehand on First, Body on Second<a class="anchor-link" href="#Body-Forehand-on-First,-Body-on-Second">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Alexander Zverev, Hyeon Chung</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [22]:</div>

</pre></div>

</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This is another cluster of players with stronger returns than serves, but these headliners are more physically imposing than those of the Body on First, Backhand on Second cluster: the headliners are taller, and the cluster on average hits faster first serves with more aces. With faster serving, players can attack a bit more on first serve and use the body serve for protection on second.</p>
<h3 id="Avoid-Forehand-on-First">Avoid Forehand on First<a class="anchor-link" href="#Avoid-Forehand-on-First">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Rafael Nadal, Jack Sock</p>

</div>
</div>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This cluster could have just as easily been called something like "Body Serves and Backhands", but the feature that really sets this group apart is their reluctance to hit to the opponent's forehand on the first serve. Players that think they have a greater advantage in neutral baseline rallies are likely to opt for serving to the body. Players that think they have a greater advantage in backhand rallies are likely to opt for serving to the backhand. Left-handed players, like Nadal, are especially likely to have a groundstroke advantage in lefty-forehand to righty-backhand exchanges.</p>
<h3 id="Spot-Serves-on-First-and-Second">Spot Serves on First and Second<a class="anchor-link" href="#Spot-Serves-on-First-and-Second">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Novak Djokovic, Roger Federer, Stan Wawrinka</p>

</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Active players in this cluster have won 38 major titles, so it's tempting to say that success requires spot serving. But it's hard to know whether this is the key to success (and Rafael Nadal, Andy Murray, Juan Martin Del Potro, and Marin Cilic suggest there are other winning styles of play). Additionally, most of the tour serves for the lines more often than not; players in this cluster just do so even more frequently, to both lines, on first and second serves.</p>
<p>Players with complete control over their servive placement and good power would likely want their opponents to defend as much of the service box as possible. This "unpredictability" in one's service placement can lead to both unreturned serves and serves that are returned but give the server a meaningful positional advantage.</p>
<h3 id="Center-Serves,-Particularly-on-Second-in-Ad-Court">Center Serves, Particularly on Second in Ad Court<a class="anchor-link" href="#Center-Serves,-Particularly-on-Second-in-Ad-Court">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Karen Khachanov, Mischa Zverev</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [25]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plot_single_cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">subset</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">cluster_labels</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">]])</span>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This is a particularly interesting cluster. The defining feature of this group of players is how they hit second serves in the ad court: a spectrum of serves to the body and down the center (to a right-hander's forehand). Mischa Zverev in particular hits down the center in that situation more than anyone else... except for Ivo Karlovic (member of Spot Serves on First and Second). It's no surprise that these two serve-and-volleyers are comfortable hitting to the forehand down the center: hitting to the center makes it more likely that the return will come down the center, making it easier to be in position for the first volley.</p>
<h3 id="Forehand-on-First,-Backhand-on-Second">Forehand on First, Backhand on Second<a class="anchor-link" href="#Forehand-on-First,-Backhand-on-Second">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Andy Murray, Marin Cilic, Grigor Dimitrov</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [26]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plot_single_cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">subset</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">cluster_labels</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">]])</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>At first glance this may seem like an odd strategy: why serve to an opponent's strength on one serve and their weakness on the other? But consider the following basic model of baseline tennis:</p>
<ol>
<li>Forehands are generally stronger than backhands</li>
<li>Stronger shots make it easier for players to capitalize on their advantage in a rally</li>
<li>Cross court exchanges are more common than non-cross court exchanges</li>
<li>Players are generally right-handed</li>
</ol>
<p>Under that basic model, you'd want to make sure you're in a forehand exchange whenever you are winning the point and in a backhand exchange whenever you are losing the point. On average, players in this cluster hit first serves at about 115 mph and second serves at about 90 mph. One could say that they are ahead in the rally whenever they complete a first serve, and behind whenever they complete a second serve. That's how you arrive at a strategy that's essentially "forehand when I'm on offense, backhand when I'm on defense".</p>
<h3 id="Body-Wide-on-First,-Body-on-Second">Body-Wide on First, Body on Second<a class="anchor-link" href="#Body-Wide-on-First,-Body-on-Second">¶</a></h3><p>Players: Joao Sousa, Lukas Rosol</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [27]:</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plot_single_cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">subset</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">cluster_labels</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">]])</span>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Neither of these players is particularly well-known. Lukas Rosol might be better known for causing Nadal's early exit from Wimbledon 2012. Joao Sousa achieved his best Slam result at the 2018 US Open, reaching the fourth round before losing to Novak Djokovic in straight sets. These players use the body serve heavily on second serve, and body-wide on first. Both players are right-handed, and their spot serving on first serve reflects the right-hander preference for spinning the ball away from their opponent's forehand on the right side of the service box (center on Ad court, Wide on deuce court). Their service placement on first serve may be a choice to keep their first serve percentage up by serving for the lines less than other better-known players.</p>
<h3 id="Wide-on-First-and-Second">Wide on First and Second<a class="anchor-link" href="#Wide-on-First-and-Second">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Daniil Medvedev</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [28]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plot_single_cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">subset</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">cluster_labels</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">]])</span>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Hitting a wide serve creates more angles for both players. If the serve is particularly strong, it can help open up the court, create a short return, and lead to a groundstroke winner. If the serve is particularly weak, it can help the opponent hit a return winner down the line. In that way, we can think of serving out wide as a way to start a shorter point where positional advantage compounds more quickly.</p>
<p>In general, the tour is more reluctant to serve out wide to the forehand side, especially on second serve. And that's where this group stands out. These players may think their advantage from their opponent being off the court is greater than the risk that their opponent hits a particularly strong forehand return.</p>
<h3 id="Not-Spot,-Not-Body">Not Spot, Not Body<a class="anchor-link" href="#Not-Spot,-Not-Body">¶</a></h3><p>Notable Players: Lucas Pouille, Gael Monfils, Roberto Bautista Agut</p>

</div>
</div>

<div class="input">

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plot_single_cluster</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">subset</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">cluster_labels</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">]])</span>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Players in this cluster still serve for the lines, but they do so less often than the rest of the tour. They also serve to the body, but they do so less often than the rest of the tour. On average, these players may be comparably worse at serving for the lines. Serving to Body/Wide or Body/Center could be an intentional choice to take less risk, or it could be the result of serving for the line and missing. The defining feature of the group may be how rarely they serve to the body on second serve, particularly in the Ad court. This could be because aiming for the body and missing is often quite costly, giving the returner an easy opportunity to go on the offensive.</p>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Kevin Anderson and Nick Kyrgios both have powerful serves. They hit an ace on about 20% of their service points, and their average first serve speeds are both in excess of 120mph. One way to make the most of a powerful serve is to hit as hard as possible down the center. Hitting to the center has two main advantages for getting aces:</p>
<ol>
<li>The ball does not have to travel as far as when serving out wide. This means the ball will reach the opponent sooner and at a speed closer to the speed with which it left the racket.</li>
<li>The net is lowest at the center of the court (3 feet high, instead of 3.5 feet at the posts). This provides more margin for error and lets the server hit down (versus out) more.</li>
</ol>
<p>If the returner does manage to get the ball back into play, serving to the center has limited the possible angles of the return. These servers are likely to get a short return in the center of the court, allowing them to go on the offensive and control the point.</p>

<p>This is a combination of a few tactics that we've already seen. Spot serves on first serve force returners to defend as much of the service box as possible. Serves out wide can create angles for both players, and serves down the center can initiate a point with a more powerful serve and a predictable return. Second serves to the backhand are common because the backhand is often the weaker groundstroke.</p>
<p>As I've mentioned before, the clusterings are relative to the rest of the tour, and this pattern is pervasive throughout almost all servers. This group could be considered "the most average", "the most by the book", or the archetype for the tour as a whole.</p>

That discussion will not conclude with this article, but I'm going to begin by showing strip plots for service outcome variables, with players separated by cluster.</p>

<h2 id="What-have-we-learned-here?">What have we learned here?<a class="anchor-link" href="#What-have-we-learned-here?">¶</a></h2><p>I started this article arguing for a theory of tennis tactics as self-selecting: players migrate to tactics that play to their relative strengths. I've clustered players by their service placement patterns and presented a visual comparison of the service outcomes for these groups.</p>
<p>Service placement patterns can be classified into 11 groups. These groups fit intuitive narratives and established assumptions about famous tennis players in the ATP tour.  There are a few key considerations that combine to create these 11 strategies, including:</p>
<ol>
<li>Players tend to vary their service placement to make it harder to hit good returns</li>
<li>Players try to hit to their opponent's weaker shot</li>
<li>Players try to position their opponents wide to open up the court for their next shot</li>
<li>Players with stronger serves use it as a weapon to shape points. Players with weaker serves try to minimize the damage their opponent can inflict with their return.</li>
</ol>
<h2 id="Just-what-is-the-relation-between-these-service-strategies-and-outcomes?">Just what is the relation between these service strategies and outcomes?<a class="anchor-link" href="#Just-what-is-the-relation-between-these-service-strategies-and-outcomes?">¶</a></h2><p>If you are particularly interested in double fault rates, you might say that double fault rates are so consistent across the tour because players select strategies that they can execute. A less likely explanation might be that double-faulting is independent of service placement decisions, or service placement decisions are so similar that the effects on double-faulting are minimal.</p>
<p>If you are particularly interested in service hold rates, you might say that hitting spot serves on first and second is the optimal strategy. I'd personally argue that you'd then need to explain why more players don't do it quite so often (although in absolute terms it is prevalent across most clusters). I'd also point out that some of the greatest male players of all time are in this group, so they might hold at higher rates due to what happens after the return is put in play. (Just based off of ace rates, it's not clear that these players get meaningfully more free points than others).</p>
<p>It's hard to know what to make of these outcomes without further analysis, but I was personally surprised by how little the different strategies vary on outcomes. It's certainly too soon to say that style differences don't cause meaningful differences in outcome, but it is also too early to say that certain widely-used tactics are ill-advised.</p>

</div>
